{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6c3f61b8-f315-465f-9fef-4395b3c80730","content":"This is a known breaking change. In .NET MAUI 10, Android uses **edge-to-edge** rendering by default, which makes the old `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` flag ineffective. The fix is to work with **window insets** instead.\n\n### Quick fix — handle IME insets on Android\n\n**1. Set `adjustResize` on your Activity** (`Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`):\n\n```csharp\n[Activity(Theme = \"@style/Maui.MainTheme\",\n          WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustResize,   // still needed as a hint\n          // ...other attributes\n          )]\npublic class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }\n```\n\n**2. Apply keyboard insets to your page's root layout.** Create a platform behavior or put this in your page's handler:\n\n```csharp\n// Platforms/Android/KeyboardInsetHandler.cs\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\nusing Microsoft.Maui.Platform;\n\npublic static class KeyboardInsetHandler\n{\n    public static void Attach(ContentPage page)\n    {\n#if ANDROID\n        var native = page.Handler?.PlatformView as Android.Views.View;\n        if (native is null) return;\n\n        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(native, new InsetListener());\n#endif\n    }\n\n#if ANDROID\n    class InsetListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n    {\n        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n        {\n            var ime    = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n            var system = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n            int bottom = Math.Max(ime.Bottom, system.Bottom);\n\n            // Convert px → DIPs for MAUI's Padding\n            float density = v.Context!.Resources!.DisplayMetrics!.Density;\n            if (v.Handler is IPlatformViewHandler handler && handler.VirtualView is ContentPage pg)\n            {\n                pg.Padding = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, bottom / density);\n            }\n\n            return insets;\n        }\n    }\n#endif\n}\n```\n\n**3. Wire it up in your chat page:**\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnHandlerChanged()\n{\n    base.OnHandlerChanged();\n    KeyboardInsetHandler.Attach(this);\n}\n```\n\n### Why this works\n\n| .NET 9 | .NET 10 |\n|---|---|\n| `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` resized the window | Deprecated in API 30; no-op with edge-to-edge |\n| Framework shrank the layout automatically | App must read `Ime()` insets and adjust padding/margin |\n\n### Alternative (simpler but less precise)\n\nIf you just want .NET 9-era behavior back, you can **opt out of edge-to-edge** in `MainActivity.OnCreate`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    // Restore pre-.NET 10 behavior\n    Window!.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(true);\n}\n```\n\nThis re-enables the old resize mode but is itself deprecated on newer Android versions, so the insets approach above is the forward-looking solution.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"47cc688f-3686-4c79-9254-25630eb9e97e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue where the keyboard covers the text input at the bottom of the screen. They mention that `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` worked in .NET 9 but doesn't work in .NET 10.\n\nThis is a known change in .NET MAUI. In .NET 9 (and earlier), Android used `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` to resize the window when the keyboard appeared. However, this API was deprecated in Android 30+ and was removed/changed in .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET 10 / .NET MAUI 10, the recommended approach is to use the `Edge-to-Edge` display mode and handle keyboard insets properly. \n\nThe core issue is that Android deprecated the resize adjustment mode in API 30, and .NET MAUI 10 switched to edge-to-edge rendering by default. The proper fix involves using the `WindowInsets` API to detect when the keyboard appears and then dynamically adjust padding on the layout to keep the input field visible. but that alone won't solve it with edge-to-edge enabled by default. The better approach for MAUI 10 is wrapping content in a `ScrollView` or leveraging the improved keyboard handling. Since edge-to-edge disables the old `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` behavior, I need to handle keyboard insets properly—either by setting `SoftInputMode` to `AdjustResize` in the Android activity while also managing the insets, or by using the newer insets API.\n\nThe cleanest path is setting up inset handling in the Android platform code to add bottom padding when the keyboard appears, or disabling edge-to-edge if that's acceptable for the design. Actually, I need to reconsider this. The real issue is that `adjustResize` doesn't play well with edge-to-edge in MAUI 10, so I should focus on using the insets API instead to properly handle keyboard overlays while keeping edge-to-edge enabled. need to manually apply window insets through a listener that captures IME and system bar insets, then adjusts the view's padding accordingly. For MAUI 10 specifically, since edge-to-edge is now the default, `WindowSoftInputMode` set to `AdjustResize` should be the primary solution, though the manual inset handling provides a fallback if that doesn't work as expected.","outputTokens":2681,"requestId":"045F:18853A:13B4FCB:160E0BD:6A027C68"},"id":"e6dc9f3a-ffde-456b-8055-708d9b80115e","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:04:29.688Z","parentId":"bd3558a0-ae66-44b1-ab97-9a35b8f779fc"}
